positions).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Merete-Van-Kamp-Pleasure-And-Pain/release/6044552|title=Pleasure and Pain|publisher=Discogs.com|accessdate=27 November 2018}}</ref> Merete Van Kamp plays in s\u00e9rie De Syv Drab 2012\n\nMerete Van Kamp is the founder of The Van Kamp Studio SAS<ref>http://www.thevankampstudio.com</ref> in Paris, France, a performing arts center and film company, currently writing directing and producing \"Theapartment\" a Drama Thriller 10 episodes TV series Season1.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|0887272}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061010065157/http://www.dr.dk/P1 Documentary (41 minutes) on DR1, Danish National talk radio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Kamp, Merete}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kolding]]\n[[Category:Danish female models]]\n[[Category:Danish television actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Danish film actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Danish actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century Danish actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Mvk00717", "label": "safe", "comment": "I CHANGED NAME OF MY S\u00c9RIE I WOULD KNOW WHAT I AM WRITING", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merete_Van_Kamp"}
{"title_page": "McNeeley Peak (Washington)", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = McNeeley Peak\n| photo = McNeeley Peak in Mount Rainier National Park.jpg\n| photo_caption = McNeeley Peak seen from the southeast\n| elevation_ft = 6786 \n| elevation_ref = <ref name=\"pb\">{{cite peakbagger|2264|McNeeley Peak, Washington}}</ref>\n| prominence_ft = 306\n| prominence_ref = <ref name=\"pb\">{{cite peakbagger|2264|McNeeley Peak, Washington}}</ref>\n| location = [[Mount Rainier National Park]]<br/>[[Pierce County, Washington|Pierce County]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| range = [[Cascade Range|Cascades]]\n| map = Washington#USA\n| map_caption = Location of McNeeley Peak in Washington\n| map_size = 250\n| label_position = right\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|46.928237|N|121.647065|W|type:mountain_region:US-WA_scale:100000_source:ngs|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] ''Sunrise'' \n| age = \n| easiest_route = [[Scrambling]] {{YDS|2}}\n}}\n'''McNeeley Peak'''<ref name=\"gnis\">\n  {{cite gnis\n  | id = 1522935\n  | name = McNeeley Peak\n  | accessdate = 2018-08-08}}</ref> is a {{convert|6,786|ft|m}} summit located in [[Mount Rainier National Park]] in [[Pierce County, Washington|Pierce County]] of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] state. It is part of the [[Sourdough Mountains]], a subset of the [[Cascade Range]]. McNeeley Peak is situated north of the [[Sunrise Historic District]], east of [[Mount Fremont]], and northwest of [[Antler Peak (Washington)|Antler Peak]]. The peak was named in 1932 for Edwin J. McNeeley (born 1858), a prominent [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]] businessman.<ref>Sketches of Washingtonians. Wellington C. Wolfe and Company (author), 1907.</ref>  Access is limited by snow closing the Sunrise Road much of the year. July, August, and September are typically the months when the Sunrise Road is seasonally open for vehicle traffic. [[Precipitation]] [[Surface runoff|runoff]] from McNeeley Peak drains into the [[White River (Washington)|White River]].\n\n==Climate==\nMcNeeley Peak is located in the [[marine west coast]] climate zone of western [[North America]].<ref name=\"Beckey, Fred W 2008\">Beckey, Fred W. Cascade Alpine Guide, Climbing and High Routes. Seattle, WA: Mountaineers Books, 2008.</ref> Most [[weather front]]s originate in the [[Pacific Ocean]], and travel northeast toward the [[Cascade Mountains]]. As fronts approach, they are forced upward by the peaks of the Cascade Range ([[Orographic lift]]), causing them to drop their moisture in the form of [[rain]] or [[snowfall]] onto the Cascades. As a result, the west side of the Cascades experiences high precipitation, especially during the winter months in the form of snowfall. During winter months, weather is usually cloudy, but, due to high pressure systems over the Pacific Ocean that intensify during summer months, there is often little or no cloud cover during the summer. Because of [[Oceanic climate|maritime influence]], snow tends to be wet and heavy, resulting in high [[avalanche]] danger.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* National Park Service web site: [http://www.nps.gov/mora/ Mount Rainier National Park]\n* Weather: [https://www.yr.no/place/United_States/Washington/McNeeley_Peak/ McNeeley Peak]\n\n[[Category:Cascade Range]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Pierce County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Mount Rainier National Park]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name = McNeeley Peak\n| photo = McNeeley Peak in Mount Rainier National Park.jpg\n| photo_caption = McNeeley Peak seen from the southeast\n| elevation_ft = 6786 \n| elevation_ref = <ref name=\"pb\">{{cite peakbagger|2264|McNeeley Peak, Washington}}</ref>\n| prominence_ft = 306\n| prominence_ref = <ref name=\"pb\">{{cite peakbagger|2264|McNeeley Peak, Washington}}</ref>\n| location = [[Mount Rainier National Park]], [[Pierce County, Washington|Pierce County]], [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| range = [[Cascade Range|Cascades]]\n| map = Washington#USA\n| map_caption = Location of McNeeley Peak in Washington\n| map_size = 250\n| label_position = right\n| range_coordinates = \n| coordinates   = {{coord|46.928237|N|121.647065|W|type:mountain_region:US-WA_scale:100000_source:ngs|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| topo = [[United States Geological Survey|USGS]] ''Sunrise'' \n| age = \n| easiest_route = [[Scrambling]] {{YDS|2}}\n}}\n'''McNeeley Peak'''<ref name=\"gnis\">\n  {{cite gnis\n  | id = 1522935\n  | name = McNeeley Peak\n  | accessdate = 2018-08-08}}</ref> is a {{convert|6,786|ft|m}} summit located in [[Mount Rainier National Park]] in [[Pierce County, Washington|Pierce County]] of [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]] state. It is part of the [[Sourdough Mountains]], a subset of the [[Cascade Range]]. McNeeley Peak is situated north of the [[Sunrise Historic District]], east of [[Mount Fremont]], and northwest of [[Antler Peak (Washington)|Antler Peak]]. The peak was named in 1932 for Edwin J. McNeeley (born 1858), a prominent [[Tacoma, Washington|Tacoma]] businessman.<ref>Sketches of Washingtonians. Wellington C. Wolfe and Company (author), 1907.</ref>  Access is limited by snow closing the Sunrise Road much of the year. July, August, and September are typically the months when the Sunrise Road is seasonally open for vehicle traffic. [[Precipitation]] [[Surface runoff|runoff]] from McNeeley Peak drains into the [[White River (Washington)|White River]].\n\n==Climate==\nMcNeeley Peak is located in the [[marine west coast]] climate zone of western [[North America]].<ref name=\"Beckey, Fred W 2008\">Beckey, Fred W. Cascade Alpine Guide, Climbing and High Routes. Seattle, WA: Mountaineers Books, 2008.</ref> Most [[weather front]]s originate in the [[Pacific Ocean]], and travel northeast toward the [[Cascade Mountains]]. As fronts approach, they are forced upward by the peaks of the Cascade Range ([[Orographic lift]]), causing them to drop their moisture in the form of [[rain]] or [[snowfall]] onto the Cascades. As a result, the west side of the Cascades experiences high precipitation, especially during the winter months in the form of snowfall. During winter months, weather is usually cloudy, but, due to high pressure systems over the Pacific Ocean that intensify during summer months, there is often little or no cloud cover during the summer. Because of [[Oceanic climate|maritime influence]], snow tends to be wet and heavy, resulting in high [[avalanche]] danger.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* National Park Service web site: [http://www.nps.gov/mora/ Mount Rainier National Park]\n* Weather: [https://www.yr.no/place/United_States/Washington/McNeeley_Peak/ McNeeley Peak]\n\n[[Category:Cascade Range]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Pierce County, Washington]]\n[[Category:Mountains of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Mount Rainier National Park]]\n", "name_user": "Ron Clausen", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/McNeeley_Peak_(Washington)"}
{"title_page": "Martin Kirkup", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          = \n| name                      =  Martin Kirkup \n| honorific_suffix          = \n| native_name               = \n| native_name_lang          = \n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                =  1948\n| baptism_date              = \n| birth_place               =  Tynemouth, Northumberland, [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| disappeared_date          = <!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place         = \n| disappeared_status        = \n| death_date                = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place               = \n| death_cause               = \n| body_discovered           = \n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments                 = \n| residence                 =  Los Angeles\n| nationality               = \n| other_names               = \n| citizenship               =  American \n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = [[University of Leicester]]\n| occupation                = Artist manager (music) \n| years_active              =  \n| employer                  = Direct Management Group\n| organization              = NARAS, BAFTA  \n| agent                     = \n| known_for                 = \n| notable_works             = \n| style                     = \n| home_town                 = \n| salary                    = \n| net_worth                 = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height                    = <!-- {{height|m=}} -->\n| weight                    = <!-- {{convert|weight in kg|kg|lb}} -->\n| television                = \n| boards                    =  \n| denomination              = <!-- Denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| spouse                    =\n| partner                   = <!-- unmarried life partner; use ''Name (1950\u2013present)'' -->\n| children                  =  \n| parents                   = \n| relatives                 = \n| awards                    = \n| signature                 = \n| signature_alt             = \n| signature_size            = \n| website                   = www.directmanagement.com\n| footnotes                 = \n| box_width                 = \n}}\n\n'''Martin Kirkup''' is a British-born music industry executive. He is a founding partner of the Los Angeles-based Direct Management Group. Over the course of his career,  Kirkup has worked with artists including [[Katy Perry]], [[Adam Lambert]], [[k.d. lang]], [[Counting Crows]], [[The B-52s]], Echo and the Bunnymen, and [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Edwards||first1=Gavin|title=One Man's Mission To Keep Musician's Legacies Alive|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/19/arts/music/dead-musician-estate-manager-joplin-doors.html?mcubz=2&_r=0|accessdate=10 July 2017|work=New York Times|date=June 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gunderson|first1=Edna|title=When it comes to new artists...Does Grammy know best? For five rising star nominees, winning the golden prize could be a mixed blessing|accessdate=|work=USA Today|date=February 19, 1999|page=1E}}</ref><ref name=\"P100\">{{cite news|last1=Billboard staff|title=Billboard Power 100|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7685115/no-78-bradford-cobb-steven-jensen-martin-kirkup-power-100|accessdate=17 June 2017|work=Billboard|date=February 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Martin Kirkup credits|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/martin-kirkup-mn0001808129|website=allmusic.com|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=10 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKirkup was born and grew up in Tynemouth, Northumberland. He attended the University of Leicester, and came to the United States in 1973 as a visiting professor at the [[University of Rhode Island]]. He later moved to New York, where he began his career in the music industry in the the publicity department at Elektra Records.<ref>{{Cite news|url=//books.google.com/books?id=dwkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=martin+kirkup+elektra+records&source=bl&ots=vIbxHVsuok&sig=P9wy6GRlClQA-Uj1Svt-ZKuQ3Hk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiWiam4lMDbAhWk3YMKHTpBAYcQ6AEISjAG#v=onepage&q=martin%20kirkup%20elektra%20records&f=false|title=Executive Turntable|last=|first=|date=November 16, 1974|work=Billboard|access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref>  \n==Career==\nKirkup was hired by A&M Records in 1975 as director of creative services.  He moved to Los Angeles in 1978, andwas named vice president of artist development, overseeing campaigns for the artists on A&M's roster, which at the time included [[Peter Frampton]], [[Nils Lofgren]], [[Supertramp]], [[Squeeze (band)|Squeeze]], [[The Tubes]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[Joe Jackson (musician)|Joe Jackson]], [[The Police]] and [[Joan Armatrading]].<ref name=\"squeeze 1981 a&m billboard\">{{cite news|last1=Kozak|first1=Roman|title=Change Brings New Ploys to Live Concerts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dyQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT7&dq=martin+kirkup&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSsJiOgsbUAhUW8mMKHVGeCaIQ6AEIPDAF#v=onepage&q=martin%20kirkup&f=false|accessdate=17 June 2017|work=Billboard|date=August 8, 1981}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, he founded Direct Management with Steve Jensen, who was previously a booking agent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/adam-lambert-splits-idol-manager-219959|title=Adam Lambert Splits With 'Idol' Manager 19 Entertainment (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en}}</ref> Kirkup and Jensen's first clients were [[Boy Meets Girl (band)|Boy Meets Girl]] and [[Nell Carter]]. Their first significant success was with [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]]; they placed \"[[If You Leave (song)|If You Leave]]\" on the ''[[Pretty in Pink (film)|Pretty in Pink]]'' soundtrack, and the song became a Top 5 hit on the [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Top 100. While the band previously had hits in Europe, the album which followed the ''Pretty in Pink'' soundtrack,  ''[[The Pacific Age]]'', was their first American gold album.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moleski|first1=Linda|title=OMD in the Spotlight|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ESUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26&dq=pretty+in+pink+OMD+kirkup&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXiqyP_f7UAhUC5GMKHRdbBUMQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=pretty%20in%20pink%20OMD%20kirkup&f=false|accessdate=10 July 2017|work=Billboard|date=October 11, 1986}}</ref>  \n\n[[Bryan Ferry]] was signed in 1988 [[Echo and the Bunnymen]] were signed in 1986,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Darling|first1=Cary|title=Hot rocks: Today, there's money to be made in selling a lot more than music|accessdate=|work=Orange County Register|date=November 6, 1988|page=KO 5}}</ref> and in 1989 Kirkup and Jensen began working with the [[The B-52's]], reformed after the death of guitarist [[Ricky Wilson (American musician)|Ricky Wilson]]. \n<ref>{{cite news|last=Graff|first=Gary|title=B-52s|accessdate=|work=Detroit Free Press|date=January 8, 1993|page=38}}</ref> Their first release as a Direct client, ''[[Cosmic Thing]]'' included the hit singles \"[[Roam (song)|Roam]]\" and \"[[Love Shack]]\" and more than 5 million copies of the album were sold. <ref name=\"Spin b52\">{{cite news|last1=Schoemer|first1=Karen|title=Beehives and Ballyhoo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CuD_QHQ-2KEC&pg=PA87&dq=martin+kirkup&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1v-z8gsbUAhUY02MKHfUbCGk4ChDoAQgrMAI#v=onepage&q=martin%20kirkup&f=false|accessdate=17 June 2017|work=Spin}}</ref> Kirkup and Jenson were credited for \"steering  (the B-52s) into a major comeback.\"<ref name=\"Selvin\">{{cite news|last1=Selvin|first1=Joel|title=Anatomy of a Hit|accessdate=|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=April 10, 1994|page=30}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992 Kirkup and Jensen signed [[The Counting Crows|Counting Crow]]; their debut, ''[[August and Everything After]]'', sold in excess of 10 million albums.<ref name=\"Selvin\" />  Direct worked with the band until 2001. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Staff|title=Counting Crows sued by former managers|url=http://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/496372/Counting-Crows-sued-by-former-managers|accessdate=10 July 2017|work=The Express|date=August 5, 2014}}</ref> They have managed Lang since signing her in 2000. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Newman|first1=Melinda|title=The Beat|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EA8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA16&lpg=PA16&dq=martin+kirkup+kd+lang&source=bl&ots=JOAtbXd3Wf&sig=TGvCS1Q5ESZe216zceiaV84fzfY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjs6Oitif_UAhUn1oMKHRwGCXY4FBDoAQgqMAI#v=onepage&q=martin%20kirkup%20kd%20lang&f=false|accessdate=10 July 2017|work=Billboard|date=August 29, 2000}}</ref>\n\nBradford Cobb joined Direct in 1997, and in 2004, he met Katy Perry and producer [[Glen Ballard]]. She was signed by Direct shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"KP billboard\">{{cite news|last1=Graff|first1=Gary|title=How Direct Management Group Helped Katy Perry Reach Her Goals|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1082842/how-direct-management-group-helped-katy-perry-reach-her-goals|accessdate=|work=Billboard|date=November 28, 2012}}</ref> The first single from the debut Katy Perry album, ''[[One of the Boys (Katy Perry album)|One of the Boys]]'', [[I Kissed a Girl]]\", became her first [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].  Her next album, ''[[Teenage Dream (Katy Perry album)|Teenage Dream]]''  became the first album by a female artist to produce five number-one ''Billboard'' Hot 100 singles  As of 2018, Perry had sold more than 100 million records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abc.go.com/shows/american-idol/news/updates/katy-perry-set-to-judge-on-abcs-american-idol|title=Katy Perry Set to Judge on ABC's American Idol {{!}} American Idol|website=ABC|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n\nDirect also manages AU/RA.  The company managed [[Adam Lambert]] from 2011 until 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wire report|title=Adam Lambert Signs with Katy Perry's Agent|url=http://www.upi.com/Adam-Lambert-signs-with-Katy-Perrys-agent/27841312643733/|accessdate=|work=UPI|date=August 6, 2011}}</ref> \n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n==External links==\n[http://www.directmanagement.com Direct Management ]\n\n[[Category:American music industry executives]]\n[[Category:Music managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix          = \n| name                      =  Martin Kirkup \n| honorific_suffix          = \n| native_name               = \n| native_name_lang          = \n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = \n| birth_date                =  1948\n| baptism_date              = \n| birth_place               =  Tynemouth, Northumberland, [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| disappeared_date          = <!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place         = \n| disappeared_status        = \n| death_date                = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place               = \n| death_cause               = \n| body_discovered           = \n| resting_place             = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments                 = \n| residence                 =  Los Angeles\n| nationality               = \n| other_names               = \n| citizenship               =  American \n| education                 = \n| alma_mater                = [[University of Leicester]]\n| occupation                = Artist manager (music) \n| years_active              =  \n| employer                  = Direct Management Group\n