9, 1999|page=1E}}</ref><ref name=\"P100\">{{cite news|last1=Billboard staff|title=Billboard Power 100|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7685115/no-78-bradford-cobb-steven-jensen-martin-kirkup-power-100|accessdate=17 June 2017|work=Billboard|date=February 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Martin Kirkup credits|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/martin-kirkup-mn0001808129|website=allmusic.com|publisher=AllMusic|accessdate=10 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKirkup was born and grew up in Tynemouth, Northumberland. He attended the University of Leicester, and came to the United States in 1973 as a visiting professor at the [[University of Rhode Island]]. He later moved to New York, where he began his career in the music industry in the the publicity department at Elektra Records.<ref>{{Cite news|url=//books.google.com/books?id=dwkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=martin+kirkup+elektra+records&source=bl&ots=vIbxHVsuok&sig=P9wy6GRlClQA-Uj1Svt-ZKuQ3Hk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiWiam4lMDbAhWk3YMKHTpBAYcQ6AEISjAG#v=onepage&q=martin%20kirkup%20elektra%20records&f=false|title=Executive Turntable|last=|first=|date=November 16, 1974|work=Billboard|access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref>  \n==Career==\nKirkup was hired by A&M Records in 1975 as director of creative services.  He moved to Los Angeles in 1978, andwas named vice president of artist development, overseeing campaigns for the artists on A&M's roster, which at the time included [[Peter Frampton]], [[Nils Lofgren]], [[Supertramp]], [[Squeeze]], [[The Tubes]], [[Brian Adams]], [[Joe Jackson]], [[The Police]] and [[Joan Armatrading]].<ref name=\"squeeze 1981 a&m billboard\">{{cite news|last1=Kozak|first1=Roman|title=Change Brings New Ploys to Live Concerts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dyQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT7&dq=martin+kirkup&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjSsJiOgsbUAhUW8mMKHVGeCaIQ6AEIPDAF#v=onepage&q=martin%20kirkup&f=false|accessdate=17 June 2017|work=Billboard|date=August 8, 1981}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, he founded Direct Management with Steve Jensen, who was previously a booking agent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/adam-lambert-splits-idol-manager-219959|title=Adam Lambert Splits With 'Idol' Manager 19 Entertainment (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en}}</ref> Kirkup and Jensen's first clients were [[Boy Meets Girl]] and [[Nell Carter]]. Their first significant success was with [[Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark]]; they placed \"[[If You Leave (song)|If You Leave]]\" on the ''[[Pretty in Pink (film)|Pretty in Pink]]'' soundtrack, and the song became a Top 5 hit on the [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] Top 100. While the band previously had hits in Europe, the album which followed the ''Pretty in Pink'' soundtrack,  ''[[The Pacific Age]]'', was their first American gold album.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moleski|first1=Linda|title=OMD in the Spotlight|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ESUEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26&dq=pretty+in+pink+OMD+kirkup&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXiqyP_f7UAhUC5GMKHRdbBUMQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=pretty%20in%20pink%20OMD%20kirkup&f=false|accessdate=10 July 2017|work=Billboard|date=October 11, 1986}}</ref>  \n\n[[Bryan Ferry]] was signed in 1988 [[Echo and the Bunnymen]] were signed in 1986,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Darling|first1=Cary|title=Hot rocks: Today, there's money to be made in selling a lot more than music|accessdate=|work=Orange County Register|date=November 6, 1988|page=KO 5}}</ref> and in 1989 Kirkup and Jensen began working with the [[The B-52's]], reformed after the death of guitarist [[Ricky Wilson (American musician)|Ricky Wilson]]. \n<ref>{{cite news|last=Graff|first=Gary|title=B-52s|accessdate=|work=Detroit Free Press|date=January 8, 1993|page=38}}</ref> Their first release as a Direct client, ''[[Cosmic Thing]]'' included the hit singles \"[[Roam (song)|Roam]]\" and \"[[Love Shack]]\" and more than 5 million copies of the album were sold. <ref name=\"Spin b52\">{{cite news|last1=Schoemer|first1=Karen|title=Beehives and Ballyhoo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CuD_QHQ-2KEC&pg=PA87&dq=martin+kirkup&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj1v-z8gsbUAhUY02MKHfUbCGk4ChDoAQgrMAI#v=onepage&q=martin%20kirkup&f=false|accessdate=17 June 2017|work=Spin}}</ref> Kirkup and Jenson were credited for \"steering  (the B-52s) into a major comeback.\"<ref name=\"Selvin\">{{cite news|last1=Selvin|first1=Joel|title=Anatomy of a Hit|accessdate=|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=April 10, 1994|page=30}}</ref>\n\nIn 1992 Kirkup and Jensen signed [[The Counting Crows|Counting Crow]]; their debut, ''[[August and Everything After]]'', sold in excess of 10 million albums.<ref name=\"Selvin\" />  Direct worked with the band until 2001. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Staff|title=Counting Crows sued by former managers|url=http://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/496372/Counting-Crows-sued-by-former-managers|accessdate=10 July 2017|work=The Express|date=August 5, 2014}}</ref> They have managed Lang since signing her in 2000. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Newman|first1=Melinda|title=The Beat|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EA8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA16&lpg=PA16&dq=martin+kirkup+kd+lang&source=bl&ots=JOAtbXd3Wf&sig=TGvCS1Q5ESZe216zceiaV84fzfY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjs6Oitif_UAhUn1oMKHRwGCXY4FBDoAQgqMAI#v=onepage&q=martin%20kirkup%20kd%20lang&f=false|accessdate=10 July 2017|work=Billboard|date=August 29, 2000}}</ref>\n\nBradford Cobb joined Direct in 1997, and in 2004, he met Katy Perry and producer [[Glen Ballard]]. She was signed by Direct shortly thereafter.<ref name=\"KP billboard\">{{cite news|last1=Graff|first1=Gary|title=How Direct Management Group Helped Katy Perry Reach Her Goals|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1082842/how-direct-management-group-helped-katy-perry-reach-her-goals|accessdate=|work=Billboard|date=November 28, 2012}}</ref> The first single from the debut Katy Perry album, ''[[One of the Boys]]'', [[I Kissed a Girl]]\", became her first [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].  Her next album, ''[[Teenage Dream]]''  became the first album by a female artist to produce five number-one ''Billboard'' Hot 100 singles  As of 2018, Perry had sold more than 100 million records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abc.go.com/shows/american-idol/news/updates/katy-perry-set-to-judge-on-abcs-american-idol|title=Katy Perry Set to Judge on ABC's American Idol {{!}} American Idol|website=ABC|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n\nDirect also manages AU/RA.  The company managed [[Adam Lambert]] from 2011 until 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wire report|title=Adam Lambert Signs with Katy Perry's Agent|url=http://www.upi.com/Adam-Lambert-signs-with-Katy-Perrys-agent/27841312643733/|accessdate=|work=UPI|date=August 6, 2011}}</ref> \n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n==External links==\n[http://www.directmanagement.com Direct Management ]\n\n[[Category:American music industry executives]]\n[[Category:Music managers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Squeeze,Brian Adams,Joe Jackson,Boy Meets Girl,One of the Boys,Teenage Dream", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Kirkup"}
